Create a typed value object for tool definitions in packages/polyglot, replacing raw OpenAI-format arrays.

## Location
packages/polyglot/src/Inference/Data/ToolDefinition.php

## Design
```php
final readonly class ToolDefinition {
    public function __construct(
        private string $name,
        private string $description,
        private array $parameters,  // JSON Schema — stays array (opaque blob forwarded to providers)
    ) {}

    public function name(): string;
    public function description(): string;
    public function parameters(): array;

    // Accepts OpenAI format: ['type'=>'function','function'=>['name'=>...,'description'=>...,'parameters'=>[...]]]
    public static function fromArray(array $tool): self;
    public function toArray(): array;  // Back to OpenAI format
}
```

## Notes
- $parameters stays array — it is an opaque JSON Schema document that formatters forward to providers. They never inspect its structure, only strip disallowed keys. Wrapping in JsonSchema would add round-trip cost with zero benefit at this layer.
- fromArray() must accept the OpenAI tool format that ToolInterface::toToolSchema() produces
- toArray() must produce the same OpenAI format for backwards compatibility

## Expected outcomes
- ToolDefinition can be constructed from name/description/parameters or from OpenAI-format array
- Round-trip: ToolDefinition::fromArray($arr)->toArray() === $arr for valid tool arrays
- No dependencies beyond packages/polyglot internals

## Acceptance criteria
1. Class is final readonly with typed accessors
2. fromArray() handles the nested ['type'=>'function','function'=>[...]] OpenAI format
3. toArray() produces valid OpenAI tool format
4. Unit test covers construction, fromArray(), toArray() round-trip
5. Parameters field is array (NOT JsonSchema) — intentional design decision

