Move the canonical ToolCall representation to packages/messages. This is the provider-agnostic representation of 'LLM wants to call this function'.

## Location
packages/messages/src/ToolCall.php

## Design
```php
final readonly class ToolCall {
    public function __construct(
        private string $name,
        private array $arguments = [],
        private ?string $id = null,
    ) {}

    public static function fromArray(array $data): self;

    public function id(): ?string;
    public function name(): string;
    public function arguments(): array;
    public function argumentsAsJson(): string;

    public function withId(string $id): self;
    public function withName(string $name): self;
    public function withArguments(string|array $args): self;

    public function toArray(): array;   // canonical: {id, name, arguments}
    public function toString(): string; // e.g. 'search(q=hello)'
}
```

## Key decisions
- ID is nullable string, NOT a ToolCallId value object — IDs can be absent (Gemini synthesizes them), and empty string validation from OpaqueExternalId is wrong at this layer
- No toToolCallArray() — that produces OpenAI Chat Completions format which is provider-specific; formatters handle that
- fromArray() accepts canonical format {name, arguments, id} — NOT the nested OpenAI {type, function: {name, arguments}} format
- arguments stored as array (JSON string parsing happens in fromArray/withArguments)
- Uses Cognesy\Utils\Json\Json for JSON parsing (same dependency as current polyglot ToolCall)

## Relationship to existing polyglot ToolCall
- The existing Cognesy\Polyglot\Inference\Data\ToolCall will be replaced by this class
- polyglot ToolCall has toToolCallArray() — that logic moves to OpenAI message formatter
- polyglot ToolCallId, ToolCallDelta, ToolCallIdByStreamIndex stay in polyglot (streaming concerns)
- A separate migration task handles updating all imports

## Acceptance criteria
1. Class is final readonly in Cognesy\Messages namespace
2. fromArray() handles {name, arguments(string|array), id} — same input flexibility as current polyglot ToolCall
3. toArray() produces {id, name, arguments(array)} — canonical, not provider-specific
4. No dependency on ToolCallId or OpaqueExternalId
5. Unit tests cover construction, fromArray, toArray round-trip, argumentsAsJson, toString

## Problem

The StepByStep::iterator() emits duplicate ContinuationEvaluated events per iteration because hasNextStep() is called twice:

1. In iterator() while condition (line 73)
2. In nextStep() match statement (line 31)

## Evidence

Log shows two identical events at step 0:
- event_id: c1fad037... ContinuationEvaluated step=0, shouldContinue=true
- event_id: 8a9ad928... ContinuationEvaluated step=0, shouldContinue=true

## Root Cause

```php
// StepByStep.php:73 - FIRST call
while ($this->hasNextStep($state)) {
    $state = $this->nextStep($state);
}

// StepByStep.php:31 - SECOND call (redundant)
public function nextStep(object $state): object {
    return match(true) {
        !$this->hasNextStep($state) => $this->onNoNextStep($state),
        // ...
    };
}
```

## Impact

- Redundant event emission (2x events per iteration)
- Potential performance impact for event listeners
- Confusing debug logs

## Suggested Fix

Option A: Cache continuation result in iterator() and pass to nextStep()
Option B: Add internal flag to skip re-evaluation when called from iterator()
Option C: Remove the hasNextStep check from nextStep() since iterator() already verified

